http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Palaeolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The Old Stone Age defined by the practice of hunting and gathering and the use of chipped flint tools. This period is usually divided up into the Lower, Middle and Upper Palaeolithic.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Lower Palaeolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The earliest subdivision of the Palaeolithic, or Old Stone Age; when the earliest use of flint tools appears in the current archaeological record. A hunter gatherer society is a defining characteristic.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Middle Palaeolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The second subdivision of the Paleolithic or Old Stone Age. Characterized by the fine flake tools of the Mousterian tradition and economically by a hunter gatherer society.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Upper Palaeolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The third and last subdivision of the Paleolithic or Old Stone Age; characterized by the development of projectile points made from bony materials and the development of fine blade flint tools.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Mesolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The Middle Stone Age, falling between the Palaeolithic and the Neolithic; marks the beginning of a move from a hunter gatherer society towards food producing society.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Early Mesolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The earliest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Late Mesolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The latest subdivision of the Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Early Prehistoric
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: For monuments which are characteristic of the Paleolithic to Mesolithic but cannot be specifically assigned.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Neolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The New Stone Age, this period follows on from the Palaeolithic and the Mesolithc and is itself suceeded by the Bronze Age. This period is characterized by the practice of a farming ecomony and extensive monumental constructions.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Early Neolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The earliest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Middle Neolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The second subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Late Neolithic
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Neolithic, or New Stone Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Bronze Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: This period follows on from the Neolithic and is characterized by the increasing use of Bronzework. It is subdivided in the Early,Middle and Late Bronze Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Early Bronze Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The earliest subdivision of the Bronze Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Middle Bronze Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The second subdivision of the Bronze Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Late Bronze Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Bronze Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Iron Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: This period follows on from the Bronze Age and is characterized by the use of iron for making tools and monuments such as hillforts and oppida. The Iron Age is taken to end with the Roman invasion.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Early Iron Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The earliest subdivision of the Iron Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Middle Iron Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The second subdivision of the Iron Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Late Iron Age
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: The third and latest subdivision of the Iron Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Later Prehistoric

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Prehistoric
http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: For monuments that can be identifed only to a date range from Palaeolithic to Iron Age.

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.label: Roman

http://perio.do/temporary/298e7714817778.note: This dates from the breakdown of Roman rule in Britain to the Norman invasion in 1066 and is to be used for monuments of post Roman, Saxon and Viking date.

source.abstract: The Digital Index of North American Archaeology (DINAA) project is developing the first online, integrated, and comprehensive database of evidence for North Americas human settlement. DINAA provides a free and open framework to examine multidisciplinary questions of human-environmental relationships, at multiple geospatial and temporal scales. The project launched in 2011 as a publicly accessible compilation of existing archaeological site file, collection, and report data from multiple regional, state, and local repositories, linked with environmental and paleoenvironmental datasets. DINAA embraces current best practices in scientific data-management. These include open standards and open licensing, transparent version control (of both data and source code), Linked Data, and iterative development. In consultation and cooperation with government, academic, and tribal stakeholders, our team is now completing the first proof of concept phase of the project. We have already linked site file information from much of the eastern United States, demonstrating the capability to develop a truly continental database.

source.abstract:
The document shows the chrono-cultural categories that are employed to classify archaeological entities within the Sistema de Informacin Arqueolgica (Archaelogical Information System, SIA+) of Incipit CSIC.
Chrono-cultural categories are not exactly periods. They have strong chronological semantics but also possess cultural meaning. This is an arguable way to categorise archaeological entities, but nevertheless they have been used by Incipit CSIC on the SIA+ for over 18 years, and currently characterise over 200.000 entities from Galicia and neighbouring areas in NW Spain.

partOf.abstract: The Greek Neolithic, here divided into five phases, is the oldest in Europe. Geographically, it is the closest to the Near East and has thus long been seen as an impoverished derivative of the latter. However, recent research has tended to emphasize the autochthonous nature of Neolithic development in Europe, including Greece. The Greek Neolithic economy, which was based almost entirely on domesticates, and its densely packed, long-lived villages strongly recall the Near East, as do also the early emphasis on fine, decorated, nonculinary pottery and the wealth of figurines. On the other hand, the evolution of stylistic patterns is specifically Greek, although generally related to trends in the Balkans. Originality in the development of the Greek Neolithic is also seen in its latest phase, with apparent decreases, rather than increases, in site density, social differentiation, and, to some extent, long-distance trade. At the same time, however, the dichotomy became much sharper between the rich agricultural plains of northern Greece and the more pastoral(?) regions of the Peloponnese and Cycladic Islands; this presages similar contrasts during the Bronze Age.
partOf.title: The Greek Neolithic: A New Review
